5 STATE OF MAINE
6 SENATE
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 756, L.D. 1949, “An Act Regarding
10 Energy Fairness”
11 Amend the bill by striking out the title and substituting the following:
12 'Resolve, Directing the Public Utilities Commission to Study Utility Service
13 Disconnections'
14 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the title and inserting the following:
15 'Sec. 1. Public utility disconnections; stakeholder discussion and
16 evaluation. Resolved: That the Public Utilities Commission shall convene a stakeholder
17 group to discuss and evaluate matters relating to public utility service disconnection
18 requirements, practices and reporting, including:
19 1. Examining whether current prohibitions on disconnections of public utility service
20 in the State adequately ensure accessibility to utility service and fairly distribute costs,
21 including those related to electric service, while considering impacts to vulnerable
22 populations;
23 2. Considering best practices related to utility service disconnections in other states
24 with similar characteristics to the State; and
25 3. Identifying strategies, making findings and developing recommendations, including
26 any necessary legislation, regarding public utility service disconnection requirements,
27 practices and reporting.
28 Sec. 2. Stakeholder group; membership. Resolved: That the Public Utilities
29 Commission shall, at a minimum, invite representatives of the following agencies, entities
30 and organizations to participate in the stakeholder group under section 1:
31 1. A statewide organization representing voters with a focus on conservation;
32 2. An organization representing the interests of older residents of the State;
33 3 A nonprofit civil legal aid and economic justice organization working to increase
34 economic security, opportunity and equity;
Page 1 - 132LR2159(03)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to S.P. 756, L.D. 1949
1 4. Each investor-owned public utility serving more than 50,000 customers in the State;
2 5. A consumer-owned public utility in the State;
3 6. A competitive electricity provider;
4 7. The Office of the Public Advocate; and
5 8. The Governor's Energy Office.
6 Sec. 3. Report. Resolved: That, by February 15, 2026, the Public Utilities
7 Commission shall submit to the Joint Standing Committee on Energy, Utilities and
8 Technology a report describing the stakeholder group's work pursuant to section 1. The
9 report must include any strategies, findings and recommendations, including any necessary
10 legislation, developed by the stakeholder group. The committee may report out a bill
11 relating to the commission's report to the Second Regular Session of the 132nd Legislature.'
12 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
13 number to read consecutively.
14 SUMMARY
1155 This amendment replaces the bill with a resolve. The amendment directs the Public
1166 Utilities Commission to convene a stakeholder group to discuss and evaluate matters
1177 related to public utility service disconnection requirements, practices and reporting. By
1188 February 15, 2026, the commission must submit to the Joint Standing Committee on
1199 Energy, Utilities and Technology a report describing the stakeholder group's work. The
2200 committee may report out a bill relating to the commission's report to the Second Regular
2211 Session of the 132nd Legislature.
